{
  "text": "In the above equation, erfc is the complementary error function, and \u2111 denotes the imaginary part. The above result holds for |\u03c7 R | \u226a s h t since we have used the expression of the propagator Eq. (10) which is only valid close to the pole. For J \u226a D, (12) is an antisymmetric function of \u03c7 R which decays as 1/\u03c7 R for \u03c7 R \u226b \u221a Dt (in agreement with Eq. (7) above), vanishes linearly for \u03c7 R \u226a \u221a Dt, and has a peak (trough) for \u03c7 \u223c \u00b1 \u221a Dt. This function is plotted in Fig. 2 . Interestingly, this shape is similar to what has been observed in [CITATION_1] .",
